## When to use
Use this skill when you need detailed insights into your system's resource usage over time, such as CPU, memory, I/O operations, network traffic, or disk space. It is particularly useful for diagnosing performance bottlenecks or during troubleshooting sessions.

## Approach
Install dstat if not already present on your Linux machine and use it to monitor various system resources simultaneously. Utilize the `shell_exec` tool from KDEV to run dstat commands with specific intervals, capturing output in real-time. Analyze the results for trends and anomalies that could indicate performance issues or resource constraints.

## Example
To continuously monitor CPU usage, memory usage, I/O operations, network traffic, and disk space every 5 seconds:
```shell
shell_exec("dstat -cdngy --noheaders --nocolor | awk '{print $1,$2,$3,$4,$6}'")
```
This command will provide a concise output of the monitored resources at regular intervals.

## Pitfalls
- Ensure dstat is installed before running commands; otherwise, an error might occur.
- Be aware that continuous monitoring with high interval frequency can introduce some system load itself.